04124nam a22004575i 9780804765138DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20221998cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047651387 a10.1515/97808047651382doi  a(DE-B1597)582480  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aHIS0220002bisacsh1 aGilman, Sander L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLove + Marriage = Death :bAnd Other Essays on Representing Difference /cSander L. Gilman. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©1998  a1 online resource (260 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStanford Studies in Jewish History and C00tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- tCHAPTER ONE Ethnicities Why I Write What I Write -- tCHAPTER TWO Love + Marriage = Death STDs and AIDS in the Modern World -- tCHAPTER THREE Max Nordau, Sigmund Freud, and the Question of Conversion -- tCHAPTER FOUR Salome, Syphilis, Sarah Bernhardt, and the "Modern Jewess" -- tCHAPTER FIVE Zwetschkenbaum's Competence Madness and the Discourse of the Jews -- tCHAPTER SIX Otto Weininger and Sigmund Freud: Race and Gender in the Shaping of Psychoanalysis -- tCHAPTER SEVEN Sibling Incest, Madness, and the Jews -- tCHAPTER EIGHT R. B. Kitaj's "Good Bad" Diasporism and the Body in American Jewish Postmodern Art -- tCHAPTER NINE Who Is Jewish? The Newest Jewish Writing in German and Daniel Goldhagen -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe essays in this collection, written by a pioneering interdisciplinary scholar, deal with the roles of images in the construction of stereotypes and the categories of difference as represented in texts—in high literature, in medical literature, in art—from the last fin-de-siècle to our own. Intensely engaged in the cultural politics of everyday life and conscious of how texts reflect and shape our social practices, they deal primarily with representations and self-representations of “Jews” in the past one hundred years and focus on the question of the constructions of the Jew’s body in art and literature. The title essay, “Love + Marriage = Death: STDs and AIDS in the Modern World,” however, studies the image of sexually transmitted disease from Shakespeare to Martin Amis. It sets the tone for an understanding of this collection as a book about Jews and their representation, but not as a special, isolated case. The first essay, the largely autobiographical “Ethnicities: Why I Write What I Write,” serves as an introduction to the collection. The other essays are: “Max Nordau, Sigmund Freud, and the Question of Conversion”; “Salome, Syphilis, Sarah Bernhardt, and the ‘Modern Jewess’”; “Zwetschkenbaum’s Competence: Madness and the Discourse of the Jews”; “Otto Weininger and Sigmund Freud: Race and Gender in the Shaping of Psychoanalysis”; “Sibling Incest, Madness, and the Jew”; “R. B. Kitaj’s ‘Good Bad’ Diasporism and the Body in American Jewish Postmodern Art”; and “Who Is Jewish?: The Newest Jewish Writing in German and Daniel Goldhagen.”  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aJewish Studies. 4aLiterary Studies -- Jewish. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476513840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804765138423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804765138/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles